[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A45"]
[Opening "Indian Defense: Accelerated London System"]
[StudyName "DrHack Explains Rating Differences/Coaching Master Class - live stream"]
[ChapterName "900 Vs 500"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/lp3DCfPj/Pbeito1U"]

{ Discussion points: Opening Knowledge }
1. d4 Nf6 { A45 Indian Game } 2. Bf4 d6 3. c3 Bf5 { No opening knowledge - 500. 900 - Systematic Opening Knowledge. } 4. e3 c6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Qc1 Nbd7 7. Nbd2 c5 8. Bg5 g6 9. e4 { 900 is able to form one move threats - and does so recklessly. } 9... Nxe4 10. Bd3 cxd4 { 500 - Neither recognizes threats against their own material with any consistency. When presented with several captures in a complex position, the 500 can not easily distinguish which is better. } 11. Bxe4 dxc3 { [%cal Ge4f5] } 12. bxc3 { Basic positional consideration like pawn structure doesn't exist yet in a 900. } 12... h6 13. Be3 { Creating a threat. } 13... Nc5 14. O-O Nxe4 { Any available capture is usually played. The idea of pins has not yet been assimilated. } 15. Bxb6 { [%csl Gb6,Ge4] } 15... axb6 16. Qc2 { Notice the basic tactics - like double attack or discovery is not yet part of the game except by accident. } 16... Ra3 17. Qb2 Rxc3 { Also removal of defender does not exist. } 18. Qb5+ Kd8 19. Qxb6+ Kc8 20. Rab1 { However the creation of a threat carries white through, since black the 500 has not yet developed this skill. This one skill + amount of game experience separates a 900 player from a 500 player on lichess. } 20... Nc5 21. Rb2 h5 22. Nb3 Bg7 23. Nxc5 Rxc5 24. Rb4 Rc7 25. a4 Bd3 26. Rd1 Be4 27. Qa7 f5 28. Ng5 Bh6 29. Ne6 Kd7 30. Nc5+ { You may think this move was played because white noticed the pin. He has no such idea in mind. The deepest a 900 player thinks is about 1/2 of a move. No opponent replies are generally considered except in extreme circumstances - like searching for checkmate. } 30... Rxc5 31. Qxb7+ { This is played because it was check. } { [%cal Ge4b7] } 31... Ke6 { 500 players do not notice misakes like hanging queens. } 32. Qb6 Rhc8 33. a5 Rc1 34. f3 Rxd1+ 35. Kf2 Rc2+ 36. Kg3 h4+ 37. Kxh4 Rh1 38. Kh3 Rg1 { A 900 player is more likely to notice hanging pieces because they are constantly searching for something to capture. } { [%cal Ge4b7] } 39. Qxg1 g5 40. fxe4 Rc3+ 41. g3 f4 42. a6 Rxg3+ 43. hxg3 g4+ 44. Kxg4 Bg7 45. a7 Bf6 46. a8=Q Ke5 47. Qaa1+ { Checkmating for a 900 is a chore. There is not yet a concept of a mating net - and only a few of the basic patterns of mate have been explored. } 47... Ke6 48. Qa2+ Ke5 49. Qd5# { White wins by checkmate. } { White stumbled onto this mate - sometimes 900 rated players don't notice it is checkmate until after it is played. There is no way to know for sure here. } 1-0


