[Opening "Van't Kruijs Opening"]
[StudyName "DrHack Explains Rating Differences/Coaching Master Class - live stream"]
[ChapterName "600 Vs 1000"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/lp3DCfPj/BoXOC0mX"]

1. e3 { A00 Van't Kruijs Opening } 1... d5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nf3 c5 4. Qa4+ { No opening theory yet for 600 players. at 1000, black has basic theoretical knowledge, but mostly plays the opening systematically. Note that lasker only used 4 opening rules originally, but coaches have expanded them any number of ways. Apply Occam's razor to your opening rule set!! The creativity of your students is higher with less rules to follow - plus there are less "rules" to give exceptions to later. } 4... Bd7 5. Qc2 Nc6 { We notice black following the systematic rules of a coach or book. Knights before bishops, develop the center, etc. } 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Qxc5 e6 { [%cal Gf8c5] } 8. Qb5 { The 600 player has now developed a basic method of making threats. Aim your piece at something it can capture safely. It just so happens that when he runs his fledgling playbook against a player following a systematic opening, the chances to win material are smaller. } 8... Ncb4 { The 1000 player has developed some basic tactics! The double attack is part of his repertoire - discovery has entered his world. Plus - A combination of these ideas has been played. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gd7b5] } 9. Qc4 Rc8 { [%csl Gc1] } 10. Qh4 Be7 { [%cal Ge7h4] } 11. Qg3 { [%csl Gc1] } 11... Rxc1+ { Black wins on time. } 0-1


