1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 { B29 Sicilian Defense: Nimzowitsch Variation, Advance Variation } 3... Nh5 { 600 - no opening book. No systematic approach to the opening. } 4. Nc3 { 1300 player developed the systematic method around 900 - 1000 and now knows some theory, which we will see in the next example. } 4... d6 5. exd6 exd6 { [%csl Gd5] } 6. Nd5 { 1300's have a sense of position. White notices the hole at d5 and plants a piece on it. } 6... Be7 7. Bb5+ Kf8 8. O-O Kg8 9. Qe2 { [%csl Ge7] } 9... h6 10. Nxe7+ { Notice again the inability to notice threats by a 600. } 10... Qxe7 11. Qxe7 Kh7 12. Bd3+ g6 13. Qxf7+ Ng7 14. Bxg6# { White wins by checkmate. } { Notice the 1300 has a strong sense of mating patterns. By this stage most 1300s have been exposed to most of the basic mates, and understand the idea of a mating net. } 1-0


