1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 { C44 King's Knight Opening: Normal Variation } 3. d3 { A danger sign. This may be an isolated event, or this 1300 has not yet started to develop an opening book. This neither fits a systematic approach, nor a theoretical book approach. It may also be a deliberate choice to leave book - in which case the warning bells can be turned off. } 3... Nf6 4. Nc3 d5 { 1800 has developed a large pool of opening knowledge. They are able to discern when moves are "strange" meaning not in this pool of knowledge. } 5. Qe2 d4 6. Nb5 Bg4 7. h3 { 1300 players are uncomfortable with pins. The reaction to a pin is often to break it at any cost. } 7... Bh5 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Bxf6 { [%cal Ge6e5,Gd5d4] } 9... Bxf6 10. g4 Bg6 11. Bg2 a6 12. g5 Be7 13. Na3 Bb4+ { 1800s have developed a basic iterative process for choosing moves. They often calculate 2-3 moves into a forced sequence, but generally do not calculate non-forced sequences. } 14. c3 dxc3 15. Nc2 cxb2+ 16. Nxb4 bxa1=Q+ 17. Qd1 Qc3+ 18. Qd2 Qxb4 19. O-O Qxd2 20. Nxd2 Qxd3 21. Rd1 O-O-O 22. Bf1 Qxd2 23. Rxd2 Rxd2 24. a4 Bxe4 25. g6 hxg6 { White resigns. } 0-1


[Event "DrHack Explains Rating Differences/Coaching Master Class - live stream: What to teach the 1300"]
[Date "2018.03.04"]
[White "What do I teach this 1300?"]
[Black "Narf"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "DrHack Explains Rating Differences/Coaching Master Class - live stream"]
[ChapterName "What to teach the 1300"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/lp3DCfPj/ZF163rBt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[UTCDate "2018.03.04"]
[UTCTime "23:29:09"]

{ This level can be reached without any further opening knowledge. 4-5 moves will suffice - usually gained through experience.

Middle Game - Tactics - as explored deliberately and not haphazardly. It is not good enough to solve automatically generated tactical problems - though these problems are great fun! In order to progress, the player needs a combination of tactics integrated into their play. It is not good enough to know pins/forks/skewers, they must be used in tandem.

This is the moment where position starts to come alive to the player: Basic positional ideas go here: weak pawns, files, squares, minor piece battles, space, time, and initiative.

End Game - The study here is preparatory for the next rating push. However,
pawn endings, Rook endings and R+Minor piece endings are the most helpful to learn here. }
 *


